  "text": "## How Kubernetes Creates a Deployment: End-to-End Flow\n\nWhen a Kubernetes client application creates a Deployment, the request flows through three distinct architectural layers: the client library, the API server, and the distributed storage system. Here is the complete technical flow:\n\n### Layer 1: Client Library (kubernetes-client-go)\n\nThe flow begins in the **kubernetes-client-go** repository, specifically in `kubernetes/typed/apps/v1/deployment.go`. The `Create` method (line 116) is the entry point. This method constructs an HTTP POST request using the RESTClient's builder pattern:\n\n```go\nfunc (c *deployments) Create(deployment *v1.Deployment) (result *v1.Deployment, err error) {\n    result = &v1.Deployment{}\n    err = c.client.Post().\n        Namespace(c.ns).\n        Resource(\"deployments\").\n        Body(deployment).\n        Do().\n        Into(result)\n    return\n}\n```\n\nThis method sends a POST request to `{apiserver}/apis/apps/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/deployments` with the serialized Deployment object.\n\n### Layer 2: API Server (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\nThe API server receives the HTTP request and routes it through multiple handler stages:\n\n#### Request Routing and HTTP Handler\nThe request is registered as a route in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/endpoints/installer.go` (line 927). The `restfulCreateResource` function wraps the handler, which ultimately calls:\n\n`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/endpoints/handlers/create.go:createHandler` (line 53)\n\nThis handler function:\n1. Extracts the namespace and name from the request (line 61)\n2. Deserializes the request body into a Deployment object (line 127)\n3. Applies admission control policies (line 203)\n4. Calls the storage layer's Create method (line 184-190):\n\n```go\nrequestFunc := func() (runtime.Object, error) {\n    return r.Create(\n        ctx,\n        name,\n        obj,\n        rest.AdmissionToValidateObjectFunc(admit, admissionAttributes, scope),\n        options,\n    )\n}\n```\n\nHere, `r` is the REST storage interface that implements the `rest.Creater` interface.\n\n#### REST Storage Layer\nThe actual storage handler for Deployments is defined in `pkg/registry/apps/deployment/storage/storage.go`. The `REST` type (line 88) is instantiated in the `NewStorage` function (line 73) and wraps a `genericregistry.Store`:\n\n```go\ntype REST struct {\n    *genericregistry.Store\n}\n```\n\nThe `genericregistry.Store` provides the Create method implementation. The store is configured with:\n- A deployment-specific `Strategy` object (line 100-102) that validates and prepares Deployments for creation\n- etcd client connection options (line 107-108)\n- Schema information for the Deployment resource (line 97-98)\n\nWhen Create is called on the Store, it:\n1. Validates the Deployment object using the Strategy (PrepareForCreate, Validate methods)\n2. Assigns system fields (generation, resource version, etc.)\n3. Calls the underlying storage backend (etcd) to persist the object\n\n### Layer 3: Storage Backend (etcd-io/etcd)\n\nOnce the API server calls the storage layer, the request is forwarded to etcd:\n\n#### etcd Server Request Handler\nIn `server/etcdserver/v3_server.go`, the `Put` method (line 157) is invoked:\n\n```go\nfunc (s *EtcdServer) Put(ctx context.Context, r *pb.PutRequest) (*pb.PutResponse, error) {\n    var span trace.Span\n    ctx, span = traceutil.Tracer.Start(ctx, \"put\", ...)\n    defer span.End()\n\n    ctx = context.WithValue(ctx, traceutil.StartTimeKey{}, time.Now())\n    resp, err := s.raftRequest(ctx, pb.InternalRaftRequest{Put: r})\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    return resp.(*pb.PutResponse), nil\n}\n```\n\nThe Put method submits the write request to the Raft consensus protocol via `raftRequest`, which ensures the Deployment data is replicated across the etcd cluster before persistence.\n\n#### MVCC Key-Value Store\nThe actual persistence is handled by the MVCC (Multi-Version Concurrency Control) key-value store defined in `server/storage/mvcc/kv.go`. The `KV` interface (line 112-134) provides the write transaction capability:\n\n```go\ntype KV interface {\n    ReadView\n    WriteView\n    Read(mode ReadTxMode, trace *traceutil.Trace) TxnRead\n    Write(trace *traceutil.Trace) TxnWrite\n    // ... other methods\n}\n```\n\nWhen the Raft consensus commits the Deployment create operation, the `Write` method creates a write transaction that:\n1. Assigns a new revision number to the Deployment key\n2. Stores the serialized Deployment under the key `\"/registry/deployments/{namespace}/{name}\"`\n3. Records this operation in the etcd backend (bbolt/boltdb)\n4. Updates the multi-version index to track resource changes\n\n### Summary of the Request Flow\n\n```\nClient Application\n         |\n         v\n[sg-benchmarks/kubernetes-client-go]\ndeployments.Create(deployment)\n         |\n         v (HTTP POST)\n[kubernetes/kubernetes - API Server]\nstaging/.../handlers/create.go:createHandler\npkg/registry/apps/deployment/storage/storage.go:REST.Create\n         |\n         v (etcd protocol)\n[etcd-io/etcd - Storage Backend]\nserver/etcdserver/v3_server.go:Put()\nserver/storage/mvcc/kv.go:KV.Write()\n         |\n         v (persisted to disk)\nbbolt backend (/var/lib/etcd)\n```\n\nThe entire flow ensures:\n- **Validation**: The Deployment is validated at the API server layer using deployment-specific rules\n- **Admission Control**: Webhooks and internal policies can intercept and modify or reject the creation\n- **Consistency**: The Raft consensus layer ensures all etcd replicas have the same data\n- **Durability**: The Deployment data is persisted to disk via the bbolt backend\n- **Versioning**: Each write increments the resource version, allowing clients to track changes\n"
